# .clauderules — Alphabet_SH Agent Working Rules

This file defines the constraints any Claude/AI agent MUST follow when modifying
code in this repository. All rules are mandatory for frontend/web changes;
violating any rule means the task is incomplete.

---

## 0. Communication Language

- **Conversation with the user:** Chinese is allowed (the user prefers Chinese
  for back-and-forth discussion).
- **All file content MUST be in English**, including:
  - Source code identifiers, string literals intended for code (not UI copy),
    log messages, and error messages.
  - All code comments (`//`, `/* */`, JSDoc).
  - Commit messages, PR descriptions, and any new Markdown/docs files.
  - File and directory names.
- UI-facing copy (text rendered to end users) may be in whatever language the
  product requires — this rule governs developer-facing text only.

---

## 1. Language & Framework

- **TypeScript is mandatory.** All new or modified source files must be
  `.ts` / `.tsx`.
- **`any` is forbidden.**
  - Do not use `any` in any form: `: any`, `as any`, `any[]`,
    `Record<string, any>`, etc.
  - When a type is unknown, use `unknown` and narrow it before use.
  - For third-party libraries without types, add a `.d.ts` declaration under
    `src/types/`. Do NOT bypass typing with `any`.
- **React component rules:**
  - Use **function components** only — class components are not allowed.
  - Manage state and side effects with **Hooks**.
  - Every component's props must have an explicit TypeScript definition
    (`interface XxxProps` or `type XxxProps`).

## 2. Coding Conventions

### Naming

- **Variables, functions, methods:** `camelCase` (e.g. `userName`, `handleClick`).
- **Module-level constants / immutable literals:** `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
  (e.g. `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`, `API_BASE_URL`).
- **React components:** `PascalCase`
  (e.g. `NavigationPicture`, `ProductSpec`).
- **Types and interfaces:** `PascalCase`
  (e.g. `ProductProps`, `UserInfo`).
- **Assets under `src/resources/`:**
  - Names must be meaningful and map clearly to the component that consumes
    them.
  - Recommended format: `<componentName>_<purpose>.<ext>`,
    e.g. `navBar_logo.png`, `productSpec_hero.jpg`.
  - Do NOT use names like `image1.png`, `IMG_0001.jpg`, or `untitled.png`.

### Async Handling

- Use **`async/await`** consistently. Do NOT chain `.then().catch()`.
- Every `await` call MUST be wrapped in a `try-catch`.
- Inside `catch`, call the **global error handler**. If it does not exist yet,
  create `src/lib/errorHandler.ts` exporting
  `handleError(error: unknown, context?: string)`.
- Example:
  ```ts
  try {
    const data = await fetchProducts();
    setProducts(data);
  } catch (error) {
    handleError(error, 'fetchProducts');
  }
  ```

### Component Reuse & File Organization

- **If reusable, extract it.** Any UI fragment or logic that appears in
  ≥2 places must be extracted into its own component / hook. No duplicated
  code (DRY).
- **File size:** A single `.tsx` file should not exceed ~300 lines. If it does,
  split it.
- **Sensible component decomposition:**
  - One component, one clear responsibility (SRP).
  - Pages (`src/pages/`) must be composed of multiple section components.
    Do NOT pile all JSX into a single page file.
  - Generic UI primitives → `src/components/ui/`.
    Business sections → `src/components/`.
- **Readability:**
  - JSX nesting depth should stay ≤ 4 levels. Beyond that, extract a child
    component.
  - Pull complex conditional renders into well-named variables or child
    components. No nested ternaries.
- **Tailwind class merging:** Always use `cn()` from `src/lib/utils.ts`.
  Do NOT manually concatenate class strings.

## 3. Project Structure

- Routes are defined in `src/App.tsx`. New pages go under `src/pages/`.
- Images:
  - Imported directly in components → `src/resources/`.
  - Referenced by URL path → `public/`.
- Styling uses Tailwind CSS 3. Custom variables live in `tailwind.config.js`;
  global base styles in `src/index.css`.

## 4. SEO, Semantics & Performance (Vite + React)

This section is specific to building public-facing pages. It compensates for
the lack of Next.js conveniences (`next/image`, automatic head management,
file-system routing metadata).

### 4.1 SEO Metadata — Per-Route Head Tags

- Every route page MUST set a unique `<title>` and
  `<meta name="description">` via `react-helmet-async`'s `<Helmet>`.
- **Title template:** `{Page Name} - {Product / Category} - Alphabet_SH`.
  Example: `Patio Mesh - Products - Alphabet_SH`.
- The root tree must be wrapped in `<HelmetProvider>` (in `src/index.tsx` or
  `src/App.tsx`).

> ⚠️ `react-helmet-async` is NOT currently installed. The first task that
> adds per-page SEO must install it (`npm install react-helmet-async` —
> requires user approval per §5) and wrap the root with `<HelmetProvider>`.

Example:
```tsx
import { Helmet } from 'react-helmet-async';

const AboutPage = () => (
  <>
    <Helmet>
      <title>About Us - Alphabet_SH</title>
      <meta name="description" content="Learn about Alphabet_SH's vision, mission, and team." />
    </Helmet>
    <main>
      <section>
        <h1>Our Vision</h1>
        <p>...</p>
        <img src="/team.webp" alt="Alphabet_SH team photo" fetchpriority="high" />
      </section>
    </main>
  </>
);
```

### 4.2 Semantic HTML

- Use semantic landmarks: `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<nav>`,
  `<header>`, `<footer>`. Do NOT default to `<div>` for structural regions.
- Each route page must have **exactly one** `<main>`.
- Heading hierarchy: one `<h1>` per page; sub-sections use `<h2>`, `<h3>` in
  order — do not skip levels.

### 4.3 Images

- **Every `<img>` MUST have an `alt` attribute.** For decorative-only images
  use `alt=""` (empty, NOT missing).
- **Above-the-fold / first viewport images:** add `fetchpriority="high"`
  (and optionally `loading="eager"`).
- **All other images:** add `loading="lazy"`.
- Provide explicit `width` and `height` when known, to avoid layout shift
  (CLS).
- This project does NOT use Next.js — `next/image` is not available. Rely on
  Vite's built-in asset hashing plus the attributes above for optimization.
  If a heavier optimization pipeline is needed later (auto-resize, WebP/AVIF
  variants), evaluate `vite-imagetools` and discuss before installing.

### 4.4 Links

- Internal navigation MUST use `<Link>` from `react-router-dom`.
  Never use a raw `<a href="/internal-path">` — it triggers a full reload
  and breaks SPA navigation.
- External links: `<a href="..." target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`.
- File downloads (PDF, etc.): `<a>` with the `download` attribute and a
  well-named filename. Filename convention: lowercase, ASCII only,
  `{topic}_{detail}.{ext}` (e.g. `product1_spec_sheet.pdf`). No spaces, no
  `IMG_0001`-style noise.

### 4.5 Breadcrumbs

- Product and category pages MUST render a reusable `<Breadcrumbs>`
  component, e.g. `Products > Industrial Mesh > Fire-retardant Series`.
- Implement once at `src/components/Breadcrumbs.tsx` and reuse — do NOT
  hand-write breadcrumb markup per page.

> Note: No `Breadcrumbs` component exists yet. The first task that needs one
> should create it as a reusable component, typed via props.

### 4.6 Structured Data (JSON-LD)

- Product pages MUST emit Schema.org `Product` JSON-LD via `<Helmet>`,
  including at minimum `name`, `image`, `description`, and `brand`.
- Centralize generation in `src/lib/schema.ts`: take typed props, return a
  `<script type="application/ld+json">…</script>` block.

> Note: No JSON-LD helper exists yet. The first product page touched after
> this rule lands should introduce `src/lib/schema.ts`.

### 4.7 Icons

- Use **SVG-based icon components only** — currently
  `@tabler/icons-react` and `@fortawesome/react-fontawesome`.
- ❌ Forbidden: icon fonts (Glyphicons, Material Icons font, etc.).
- For one-off custom icons, place an SVG under `src/resources/` and import
  it, or inline the SVG markup.

---

## 5. Agent Workflow Rules

### Before Editing

1. Run `ls` first to confirm the target directory structure exists, so files
   are not created in the wrong place.
2. For any existing file you intend to modify, `Read` the full file first.
   Do not edit blindly.

### After Editing

1. Run the self-check commands:
   ```bash
   npm run lint        # ESLint (config: eslint.config.mjs)
   npm run typecheck   # tsc --noEmit
   ```
2. If lint or typecheck reports an **error**, fix it before delivering. Do not
   ship code with errors. Warnings should be addressed when touching the
   relevant file (Boy-Scout rule) but are not strictly blocking.
3. `npm run lint:fix` auto-fixes formatting-level issues; review the diff
   before committing.
4. For UI changes, verify the golden path under `npm start`
   (Vite dev server at `http://localhost:5173`). If verification is not
   possible, say so explicitly.

### Fix-on-Touch (Boy-Scout Rule, mandatory)

When you modify a file for any task, audit **that file** against §1–§4 and
fix any rule violations you can fix without expanding the scope of the task.
Common things to clean up opportunistically:

- `<img>` missing `alt`, `loading`, or (for above-the-fold) `fetchpriority`
- Generic alts like `"Product"`, `"SPEC1"`, `"Image"` — rewrite to be
  meaningful
- `<div>` used where `<main>` / `<section>` / `<header>` / `<footer>` /
  `<nav>` is the correct semantic landmark
- Missing `<Helmet>` on a route page
- Untyped props, `any` slips, lingering `@ts-ignore`
- Internal navigation using raw `<a href="/...">` instead of `<Link>`
- Duplicated logic / inline component definitions that can be split out
  within the same file
- Missing `loading="lazy"` on below-the-fold media

Do **NOT** chase violations into other files in the same change — that
becomes a separate refactor task and should be discussed with the user.
**Note the opportunistic cleanup in your response and commit message** so
the diff isn't a surprise to reviewers.

### Git / Shell Safety

- Never use `--no-verify` to skip hooks.
- Do not run irreversible operations (`git push`, `git reset --hard`,
  `rm -rf`, force-push, etc.) without explicit user approval.
- Do not `npm install` new dependencies without asking first. If a new
  dependency is genuinely required, explain why and request approval.

## 6. Forbidden

- ❌ Using `any`, `@ts-ignore`, or `@ts-nocheck` to bypass the type system.
  In rare unavoidable cases, use `@ts-expect-error` with a comment explaining
  why.
- ❌ Copy-pasting duplicated code blocks instead of extracting an abstraction.
- ❌ Cramming multiple independent components into a single file.
- ❌ Delivering code that has not been type-checked.
- ❌ Editing / writing a file without reading it first.

---

> These rules apply to all AI agent work in this repository. To adjust them,
> edit this file directly and note the change in the commit message.
